fix:
private static final int STATE_START = 1;  

public long getElapsedTime(){  
    switch(runningState){  
        case STATE_START:{  
            return now();  
        }  
        case STATE_PAUSED:{  
            return lastStart+split() - pausedAt;  
        }  
    }  
    return lastStart + elapsed() - pausedAt;  
}  

private static long now() {  
    return System.nanoTime() / 1000000L;  
}  

private static long elapsed(long nanos) {  
    return now() - nanos;  
}  

public void resume() {  
    if (!canResume()) throw new IllegalStateException("Cannot resume "+ this );  

    runningState--;
    pausedAt = 0;  
}  

public boolean canSuspend() {  
    return runningState == STATE_START;  
}  

public void suspend() {  
    if(!canSuspend()) throw new IllegalStateException("Cannot suspend" + this);  
    runningState++;  
    pausedAt = now();  
    start();  
}  

protected synchronized boolean canResume() {  
    return runningState > STATE_START ;  
}  

public synchronized boolean canStop() {  
    return runningState >= STATE_START;  
}

issue_description:
In my opinion, it is a bug that suspend() acts as split(), if followed by stop(); see below:
        StopWatch sw = new StopWatch();
        sw.start();
        Thread.sleep(1000);
        sw.suspend();
        // Time 1 (ok)
        System.out.println(sw.getTime());
        Thread.sleep(2000);
        // Time 1 (again, ok)
        System.out.println(sw.getTime());
        sw.resume();
        Thread.sleep(3000);
        sw.suspend();
        // Time 2 (ok)
        System.out.println(sw.getTime());
        Thread.sleep(4000);
        // Time 2 (again, ok)
        System.out.println(sw.getTime());
        Thread.sleep(5000);
        sw.stop();
        // Time 2 (should be, but is Time 3 => NOT ok)
        System.out.println(sw.getTime());
suspend/resume is like a pause, where time counter doesn't continue. So a following stop()-call shouldn't increase the time counter, should it?

